missions.help_text: Speak and write using correct grammar.  Understand and use new vocabulary.
Recognize units of measure and solve problems involving measurement.
This is a short mission. It should be paired with 8th Grade Statistics and Probability.

domains.description: Number and Operations in Base Ten

standards.description: Interpret and compute quotients of fractions, and solve word problems involving division of fractions by fractions, e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem.
Convert among different-sized standard measurement units within a given measurement system (e.g., convert 5 cm to 0.05 m), and use these conversions in solving multi-step, real world problems.
Compare and contrast the adventures and experiences of characters in stories.
Recognize common types of texts (e.g., storybooks, poems).

Understand that the probability of a chance event is a number between 0 and 1 that expresses the likelihood of the event occurring. Larger numbers indicate greater likelihood. A probability near 0 indicates an unlikely event, a probability around 1/2 indi
Distinguish among the connotations (associations) of words with similar denotations (definitions) (e.g., refined, respectful, polite, diplomatic, condescending).
Analyze how visual and multimedia elements contribute to the meaning of a text.
Spell grade-appropriate words correctly, consulting references as needed.
Recognize and correct inappropriate shifts in pronoun number and person.

Use addition and subtraction within 20 to solve word problems involving situations of adding to, taking from, putting together, taking apart, and comparing, with unknowns in all positions, e.g., by using objects, drawings, and equations with a symbol for

The Fantastic Flying Books of Mr  Morris Lessmore
Morris
activities.instructions: Read the book. Answer the following questions: What are the important differences between the book and the movie? How did each version impact the story in different ways?

activities.title: The Muppets - The Emperors New Clothes
The Emperor's New Clothes
activities.instructions: As you read this story, visualize it in your head.  Answer the following questions: What does it look like? Then, watch (or rewatch) "The Emperor's New Clothes" video clip. How is reading the story different from watching the movie? What are you able to see and hear in the movie that you cannot in the text?

activities.title: All Summer in a Day
activities.instructions: What is the theme of this story? How does the author's writing convey the theme?

activities.title: The Quiet World
activities.instructions: How is the theme of this story different from "All Summer In a Day"? How is it similar?

activities.title: Aesop
activities.instructions: Read "The Stag & His Reflection." How is the topic of this fable similar to the topic in the myth of Narcissus? How is it different?

activities.title: Sleuthy Gumshoe: The Remarkable Detective
activities.instructions: Read two of the detective stories in this book. What is the topic of each story? How does the author develop the topic over the course of the story?

activities.title: Kitsville Caper
activities.instructions: How are the patterns of events in the Sleuthy Gumshoe stories and "The Kitsville Caper" similar? How are they different? Are these two texts about the same topic? Why or why not?

activities.title: Doceri
activities.instructions: Select one of the pairs of texts you read in this quest - "All Summer In A Day" and "The Quiet World"; "Narcissus and Echo" and "Aesop for Children: The Stag & His Reflection"; or "The Kitsville Caper" and "Sleuthy Gumshoe:The Remarkable Detective." Make a presentation comparing both the theme and the topic of the two texts. Then discuss how the authors used different styles and approaches to convey the theme and topic.

Oz
activities.instructions: Select "Read it Myself".  Read the story.  From who's point of view is the story told?  In order to make it first-person narration, who would tell the story?

activities.title: Mulberry St.
activities.instructions: Select "Read it Myself".  Read the story.  Who is the narrator in this story?  How would the story be different if it was told by someone else?

quests.short_description: At the end of this quest, you will be able to determine an author's point of view or purpose for writing a text as well as analyze conflicitng viewpoints.

activities.title: Asking and Answering Questions for Reading Comprehension
The Revolution
activities.instructions: Read pages 10-19.  Why did the author include this section in the book? Provide evidence from the text to support your reasoning.

activities.title: ACT Science: How to Answer Questions on Opinions & Conflicting Viewpoints | Kaplan Test Prep
Loyalist (American Revolution)
activities.instructions: Read about the Loyalists' perspective on the American Revolution.  As you read, stop when you come to a word, phrase, or sentence you don't understand.  Write a question about what is confusing to you.  What did the Loyalists' believe were the causes for the American Revolution?  How does their perspective conflict with the view point of the Patriots?

activities.title: Anonymous account of the Boston Massacre March 5 1770
activities.instructions: Read the "Anonymous Account of the Boston Massacre".  Describe the author's point of view and purpose for writing the text.  Is his point of view objective?  What questions do you still have after reading the text?

activities.title: Keynote
activities.instructions: Using information from the apps, create a Keynote that conveys your point of view on The Revolutionary War or the events that led up to the war.  Use evidence to support your point of view.  Be sure to aknowledge opposing viewpoints and refute them.

activities.title: eSpark Learning: Differentiate facts and opinions framing video (FA13, Quest 8, 8.RI.8/8.RI.9)
Galaxies by KIDS DISCOVER
activities.instructions: Tap Index.  Select 6.  Read “Galactic Myths and Legends.” Explain how different cultures see the Milky Way.  What is a possible reason there are so many different interpretations of the same thing?

activities.title: NASA - Why explore space?
activities.instructions: Read the article. How does the author use a mixture of facts and opinions to present his argument? Select 2 facts and 2 opinions. How did you know which were facts and which were opinions? Write your response in your reading journal.

activities.title: Galaxies by KIDS DISCOVER
activities.instructions: Tap Index.  Select 3.  Read about Exotic Galaxies.  What piece of information did scientists learn in 1963 that changed their thinking about the strange stars they discovered in 1960?

activities.title: Draft a thesis statement--Lesson 2 of 7 (Common Core Standard W.8.1a)
Doceri
activities.instructions: Present your own opinion of space exploration.  Select one of the techniques of persuasive writing to support your opinion.  Be sure to include the opinions of the authors and the evidence they use to support their opinions.
